<div class="topic-content col-sm pr-lg-60">

	    <!--[BEFORE-ARTICLE]--><!DOCTYPE HTML><span class="marker before-article"></span><section id="ref1" data-level="1"><p><strong><span id="ref672371"></span>Steve Jobs</strong>, in full <strong>Steven Paul Jobs</strong>,  (born February 24, 1955, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/San-Francisco-California" class="md-crosslink autoxref">San Francisco</a>, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/California-state" class="md-crosslink autoxref">California</a>, U.S.—died October 5, 2011, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Palo-Alto" class="md-crosslink autoxref">Palo Alto</a>, California), cofounder of Apple Computer, Inc. (now <span id="ref672372"></span><a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Apple-Inc" class="md-crosslink">Apple Inc.</a>), and a <a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/charismatic" class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off" data-term="charismatic">charismatic</a> pioneer of the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/technology/personal-computer" class="md-crosslink">personal computer</a> era.</p><!--[P1]--><span class="marker p1"></span><!--[AM1]--><span class="marker AM1 am-inline"></span><script type="application/ld+json">
	{
